{
  "text": "In the CNS, microglial cells, astrocytes, and neurons are susceptible to T. gondii infection, and in chronic infections, latent cysts are produced in the CNS [CITATION_1] . Although microglial cells are largely responsible for preventing T. gondii proliferation in the brain, they also sometimes produce the anti-inflammatory cytokine IL-10, and facilitate parasite persistence by suppressing immune responses in the CNS [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . IL-10 is produced mainly by brain mononuclear cells, and inhibits the productions of IL-12, IL-6, IFN-c, and TNF-a, suggesting that IL-10 has an ameliorative effect on the severe inflammation caused by toxoplasmic encephalitis [CITATION_4] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "2883627",
